{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"841dd1e8-415c-4c52-a04a-109e9bd6d814","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p $(pidof dotnet) --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening `trace.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools, use the **sidecar** approach or a [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting.\n- If the issue is **CPU spikes**, consider `dotnet-counters` first to confirm which metrics are elevated before tracing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"336268ac-2a9c-4f8b-900a-e88ccf2b03d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":395,"requestId":"640F:131578:151E1C6:187621C:69EC159B"},"id":"c09c2d70-7e20-4a10-ae9b-9a1925540fb4","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:15:16.337Z","parentId":"aa9b5b1d-915d-4d0c-a545-a9373b9ca071"}
